DescriptionOfSpecies: About 2 ft tall. Alternate arrangement with three nerved leaves. Set of leaves below flower is opposite. Seed is ~1/3 inch. Has small spokes at top and is green-brown.

CollectionLocality: Chisholm Creek off of N Chisholm Creek Rd, near Lawrenceburg, TN
LocationDetails: Park along N Chisholm Creek Rd and walk south in Chisholm Creek, paying attention to west bank
HabitatGroup: Inland surface waters
NotesonHabitatorSoil: Loam, silt soil. Found along west side of creek only.
OtherCollectionInformation: There are 15 maternal lines associated with this collection. The DNA collected corresponds to Material line 1, 5, and 8.

DescriptionOfSpecies: Stems have alternate leaf arrangement, leaf veins depressed, lanceolate. Seed heads are radially symmetrical, about 1/2 inch in diameter, green to brown. Stems 12-24 inches in length.
AssociatedSpecies: Fagus sp. (beech), Carpinus caroliniana (musclewood), Platanus cashmeriana (sycamore), Cornus sp. (dogwood), Hamamelis sp. (witch hazel), ferns, moss, liverworts, Bouteloua sp. (sideoats), Asters sp., Rudbeckia sp.
LocationDetails: South of intersection of Finnie Road and Armetis Ln, along west bank of Gildridge Branch creek
HabitatGroup: Inland surface waters
NotesonHabitatorSoil: Loam, silt soil. Near water. Creek is cold temperature, possibly spring fed. Soil is loamy silt. Plant occurs on somewhat thin soils alongside moss and ferns.
OtherCollectionInformation: Found along west side of creek only. Creek stomping inevitable, bring water shoes. Also lookout for venomous snakes. Creek rocks can be very slick. There are 12 maternal lines associated with this collection. The DNA collected corresponds to Material line

DescriptionOfSpecies: Erect stems up to 10cm. Single whorl of 3 entire petiolate foliage. Petiole 3-4mm long, mostly glabrous. Inflorescence includes solitary terminal flower erect/ascending above leaves. Fruit is ovoid to ellipsoid berry, nodding below leaves.
AssociatedSpecies: Staphylea trifolia, Tilia americana, Ribes hirtellum, Sanguineria canadensis, Podophyllum peltatum, Arisaema triphyllum
LocationDetails: 3867 N Hwy 79, Elsberry.  Highway 79 one mile north of Elsberry.  The property is on the west side of 79.
HabitatGroup: Woodland, forest and other wooded land
NotesonHabitatorSoil: Minimally disturbed woodland. Steep inclines cover property. Area is burned at regular intervals. Kudzu introduced as erosion control.

DescriptionOfSpecies: Erect stems up to 10cm. Single whorl of 3 entire petiolate foliage. Petiole 3-4mm long, mostly glaborus. Inflorescence includes solitary terminal flower erect/ascending above leaves. Fruit is ovoid to ellipsoid berry, nodding below leaves.

LocationDetails: 5151 CO Rd, 322 Palmyra MO. Site is located in wooded area beyond pasture towards river.
HabitatGroup: Woodland, forest and other wooded land
NotesonHabitatorSoil: Semi-dense woodland severely disturbed due to cattle grazing. Steep incline with talus piles at base and up slope. Limestone and dolomite deposits were present. Deep ravines emptied into nearby river.
OtherCollectionInformation: Population largely contained immature fruit. Individuals sampled was reduced from expected quota.
